Step 2: Describe the procedures that were used to collect the data.

a) Report the study design that generated that data (for example: data reporting, surveys, observation, experiment).

data reporting


b) Describe the original purpose of the data collection.

It seeks to increase the use and understanding of statistics about social, economic, and environmental development at local, national, and global levels.


c) Describe how the data were collected.

The data source of the income data is World Bank Work Development. 

The data source of The alcohol consumption data is WHO. alcohol consumption per adult (age 15+), litres was Recorded and estimated average alcohol consumption. 

The data source of the life expectancy data are 1. Human Mortality Database, 2. World Population Prospects: 3. Publications and files by history prof. James C Riley 4. Human Lifetable Database.   
life expectancy at birth (years) was the average number of years a newborn child would live if current mortality patterns were to stay. 

The data source of the urban rate is World Bank. Urban population refers to people living in urban areas as defined by national statistical offices (calculated using World Bank population estimates and urban ratios from the United Nations World Urbanization Prospects).  



d) Report when the data were collected.

The income data was collected in 2010.
The alcohol consumption data was collected in 2008.
The life expectancy data was collected in 2011.
The urban rate data was collected in 2008.

e) Report where the data were collected.

All 192 United Nation members and total 215 areas.
